{
  "doc_id": "6119",
  "text": "Health-related quality of life (HRQL) refers to the effects of health, illness and treatment on perceived quality of life (Ferrans et al., 2005) . SES has previously been described to affect HRQL in a nationally representative cohort of Canadian adults [CITATION_1] , in adults with a chronic disease in Germany [CITATION_2] , and among males (but not females) in Japan (Yamazaki, Fukuhara & Suzukamo, 2005) . Among patients with rheumatoid arthritis and other chronic conditions, there was evidence that lower income was associated with poorer HRQL (Alishiri et al., 2008; [CITATION_3] , but females made up the vast majority of both study populations. Of note, in the USA, disparities in self-rated health when stratified by income group were widest in adults aged 45 to 54 years [CITATION_4] . Previous studies have also indicated that poorer SES is associated with adverse metabolic outcomes, but two of these studies observed this association only among women (Chichlowska et al., 2008; Lim et al., 2012) , with a third investigation showing only a week association among male participants [CITATION_5] .",
